@segment
Contrarian Questions
CQ

@package
The Question Nobody Wants to Answer
Free

@text
There is a kind of question most people refuse to answer in public.
Not because the answer is embarrassing.
Because answering it out loud would put you in disagreement with everyone you know.
Silence is cheaper.
Silence is also why most interesting ideas never get tested.

@text
Suppose you are allowed to believe one fact about the world that almost nobody agrees with.
Not a strange belief about aliens.
A specific, testable belief about how something works.
You could defend it to a roomful of people if they asked.
Most of the room will disagree. Almost all of them will be polite about it.
Hold that belief in your head as the premise.

@text
Now add a condition.
The belief has to be one that, if true, would change how you spend the next 10 years.
Not a minor preference.
A fact that, once you accept it, forces you to do different work than everyone around you.
Most beliefs do not clear this bar.
Most opinions would not change your Monday morning if they turned out to be correct.

@text
If you can name a belief that passes that test, one of two outcomes follows.
Either you are wrong and the world is right. You will learn quickly and move on.
Or you are right and the world is wrong.
You are sitting on an opportunity almost nobody is competing with.
The second outcome builds the valuable companies and the important research.
These ideas are not obvious in advance.
The honest answer to the question is uncomfortable to say.

@question
There is a famous question in business: "What important truth do very few people agree with you on?" Why is this question harder to answer than it looks?

answer: Because the honest answer puts you in disagreement with most people you know, which is socially expensive.
consequence: That is the real reason. The question is not hard to think about. It is hard to say out loud.

answer: Because it is hard to know what is actually true.
consequence: Knowing what is true is hard, but that is not what stops people. Plenty of people are confident. The bottleneck is whether they will say it.

answer: Because most people do not have enough information to have beliefs.
consequence: Everyone has beliefs. The problem is not having them. The problem is voicing the unpopular ones.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: This question filters for founders. Answering it honestly takes the same social courage as building a contrarian company.
hint: The question is not about knowing a truth, but about saying one.

@text
This question is the central exercise behind the idea.
Every valuable new business is built on a <c:g>secret</c:g>.
A secret is a fact the founder believes that most people do not yet agree with.
If the fact is obvious, someone else has already built the business.
If it is just a preference, it will not survive contact with reality.

@true_false
If everyone around you agrees with your business idea, that is a good sign, because it means the idea is sound.

true: True, agreement is a sign of a good idea.
consequence: Agreement is a sign you are saying something familiar. Familiar ideas rarely create anything new.

false: False, universal agreement means the idea is crowded.
consequence: Right. A truly new business needs a fact not yet widely accepted. If your idea gets instant agreement, it is probably already being built.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Being right when most people are wrong is the goal. Agreement is just a signal that you have not stepped outside what is already being built.
hint: Ask whether an idea everyone agrees with has any room for a new company.

@reflect
A belief about your work that you hold privately but have never defended out loud: an industry assumption you think is wrong.
A belief that, if true, would change how you spend your next Monday morning: a different product, a different audience.
An action that belief would lead to tomorrow, if you treated it as true: a conversation, a prototype, or a written plan.
